eins","Superior cerebral veins"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eunion of internal cerebral veins\u003C/strong\u003E forms the great cerebral vein. These internal cerebral veins drain deep structures of the brain including the choroid plexus, thalamus and basal ganglia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eunion of superior sagittal sinuses\u003C/strong\u003E is anatomically incorrect as there is only one superior sagittal sinus, and it does not form the great cerebral vein. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eunion of basal veins\u003C/strong\u003E does not form the great cerebral vein, though the basal veins do drain into it. \u003Cstrong\u003ECortical veins\u003C/strong\u003E are superficial vessels that drain into the dural venous sinuses rather than forming the great cerebral vein. \u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior cerebral veins\u003C/strong\u003E are also superficial structures that drain into the superior sagittal sinus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe great cerebral vein continues posteriorly to join with the inferior sagittal sinus, forming the straight sinus which ultimately drains into the transverse sinus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The great cerebral vein is formed by the union of the two internal cerebral veins.","The internal cerebral veins drain deep structures including the choroid plexus, thalamus and basal ganglia.","The great cerebral vein joins with the inferior sagittal sinus to form the straight sinus."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98413"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18647"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98413"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09